de.esoco.lib.datatype

Class ObjectId<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • de.esoco.lib.datatype.ObjectId<T>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    ObjectId.IntegerId, ObjectId.LongId, ObjectId.StringId

    public abstract class ObjectId<T>
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.io.Serializable
    A generic representation of a unique object identifier. How exactly an object ID is defined and in which context it is unique depends on the concrete subclasses. This base class defines the general properties of object IDs:
    1. Each object ID must have a string representation that is considered to be equivalent to the object ID instance itself. To enforce this fact the methods equals(Object) and hashCode() are overridden as final and are based on the result of the IDs toString() method. It is advised to use a readable string representation for all implementations.
    2. An object ID represents a certain type of object that is indicated by the generic type parameter T. This type can be used by applications to define generic methods or classes that accept or return objects only if it matches the generic type of an ID that it is associated with. See below for a further explanation of the restrictions of this generic type.
    3. The internal representation of an object ID implementation is not used for the general handling of IDs. But for some applications, e.g. storage frameworks, it may be necessary to know the internal value of an ID. For such purposes the method internalValue() provides access to that value. Implementations of this method should only return immutable objects.

    Because of these properties it is recommended to reference even the instances of subclasses only as ObjectId. To simplify this kind of usage this class contains factory methods that create new ID instances for different value types. This scheme of instance creation should be repeated by application-specific ID implementations.

    The generic type of an object ID has no internal meaning for the ID instance itself. It is only declarative and provided to reduce the necessity of explicit type casts when using object ID constants to access the associated objects. This will reduce possible class cast errors when a referenced type changes because by using object IDs the types of values will be enforced automatically on both setting and querying. To support this generic object ID usage the corresponding interfaces must be implemented cautiously. Most importantly they should implement symmetric generic methods to set and query objects based on the generic type of an object ID to ensure that the same type is used in both directions.

    Due to the generic type erasure any access based on the generic type of an object ID will be replaced by a corresponding type cast. That means that using a certain object ID to access an object of a different type will result in a ClassCastException being thrown. Therefore, if the type is not exactly known an unspecific ID type like ObjectId<?> should be used instead. Generally speaking, using an object ID with a specific type is the same as applying a type cast and must therefore be performed with exactly the same precautions.
